## Communication preferences

The rules in `~/.claude/rules/` govern Claude's tone and end-of-turn output:

- `no-glazing.md` — no filler agreement; disagree in the first sentence
- `proof-of-work.md` — actively verify before claiming done; emit a
  `Proof of Work:` section at the end of any turn that modified files
  (also enforced by the Stop hook)
- `whats-next.md` — every turn ends with a `What's Next:` block
- `commit-discipline.md` — wait for explicit authorization before any
  `git commit` / `git push`

See [WHY.md](https://github.com/uplifting-tspann/claude-code-starter/blob/main/WHY.md)
for the reasoning behind each. If you've adapted this starter, change the
URL above to your fork.

## Persistent memory

Claude Code stores cross-session memory at:

```
~/.claude/projects/<project-folder>/memory/
```

Each project gets its own `MEMORY.md` index + per-topic files. Run
`/consolidate-memory` regularly (or wire it to a nightly schedule) so the
index stays curated rather than bloated.

